04655nam a22005055i 9780822389897DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223898977 a10.1515/97808223898972doi  a(DE-B1597)552340  a(OCoLC)1125905005  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.897/0794732221 aRamirez, Renya K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNative Hubs :bCulture, Community, and Belonging in Silicon Valley and Beyond /cRenya K. Ramirez. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b9 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Disciplinary Forces and Resistance: The Silicon Valley and Beyond -- t2 Gathering Together in Hubs: Claiming Home and the Sacred in an Urban Area -- t3 Laverne Roberts's Relocation Story: Through the Hub -- t4 Who Are the "Real Indians"? Use of Hubs by Muwekma Ohlones and Relocated Native Americans -- t5 Empowerment and Identity from the Hub: Indigenous Women from Mexico and the United Slales -- t6 "Without Papers": A Transnational Hub on the Rights of Indigenous Communities -- t7 Reinvigorating Indigenous Culture in Native Hubs: Urban Indian Young People -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost Native Americans in the United States live in cities, where many find themselves caught in a bind, neither afforded the full rights granted U.S. citizens nor allowed full access to the tribal programs and resources-particularly health care services-provided to Native Americans living on reservations. A scholar and a member of the Winnebago Tribe of Nebraska, Renya K. Ramirez investigates how urban Native Americans negotiate what she argues is, in effect, a transnational existence. Through an ethnographic account of the Native American community in California's Silicon Valley and beyond, Ramirez explores the ways that urban Indians have pressed their tribes, local institutions, and the federal government to expand conventional notions of citizenship.Ramirez's ethnography revolves around the Paiute American activist Laverne Roberts's notion of the "hub," a space that allows for the creation of a sense of belonging away from a geographic center. Ramirez describes "hub-making" activities in Silicon Valley, including sweat lodge ceremonies, powwows, and American Indian Alliance meetings, gatherings at which urban Indians reinforce bonds of social belonging and forge intertribal alliances. She examines the struggle of the Muwekma Ohlone, a tribe aboriginal to the San Francisco Bay area, to maintain a sense of community without a land base and to be recognized as a tribe by the federal government. She considers the crucial role of Native women within urban indigenous communities; a 2004 meeting in which Native Americans from Mexico and the United States discussed cross-border indigenous rights activism; and the ways that young Native Americans in Silicon Valley experience race and ethnicity, especially in relation to the area's large Chicano community. A unique and important exploration of diaspora, transnationalism, identity, belonging, and community, Native Hubs is intended for scholars and activists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822389897zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822389897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/cover